            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; color: #999999; margin: 0 0 24px 0;">Sources: ONS House Price Index Q4 2025, Rightmove sold prices 2025, NAEA Propertymark regional data. Typical offer ranges reflect accepted offers, not initial bids.</p>

      <figure style="margin: 0 auto 24px; max-width: 720px;">
        <img src="/images/buying-guide/cheshire-offer-dynamics-comparison.webp" alt="Cheshire offer dynamics comparison showing three market tiers - Golden Triangle at 95-102% of asking price with high competition, Mid-Cheshire at 92-97% with medium competition, and Affordable Cheshire at 88-95% with low-medium competition" loading="lazy" width="720" height="443" style="width: 720px; max-width: 100%; aspect-ratio: 720/443; border: 1px solid #E5E0D8;" />
        <figcaption style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; color: #999999; margin-top: 8px;">Cheshire property offer ranges vary significantly by market tier - Golden Triangle buyers compete at or above asking price while affordable areas offer 5-12% negotiation room.</figcaption>
      </figure>
      <h3 style="font-family: Georgia, serif; font-size: 20px; font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; margin: 24px 0 12px 0;">Golden Triangle - Wilmslow, Knutsford, and Alderley Edge</h3>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Golden Triangle properties attract multiple offers within the first two weeks of listing, particularly detached homes with four or more bedrooms (Rightmove, 2025). Wilmslow averages £550,000 with turnkey properties under 14 days on market rarely accepting below asking price.</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Knutsford's period properties on King Street and around The Heath command a historic character premium that pushes offers to 97-100% of asking. Alderley Edge operates at the prestige end with entry prices at £700,000 and the top market ranging from £3,000,000 to £7,000,000.</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0;">Sealed bids are a regular occurrence in the Golden Triangle. Estate agents trigger the process when three or more buyers express interest, setting a best-and-final deadline. Buyers competing for Golden Triangle properties benefit from being chain-free, having a mortgage offer (not just an AiP), and naming their solicitor upfront. <a href="/buying-guide/stamp-duty-cheshire" style="color: #3D5A3E;">SDLT on Golden Triangle properties</a> ranges from £17,500 at Wilmslow's average to £43,750 at £1,000,000 - factor this into your total budget ceiling.</p>

      <h3 style="font-family: Georgia, serif; font-size: 20px; font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; margin: 24px 0 12px 0;">Mid-Cheshire - Chester, Macclesfield, and Frodsham</h3>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Chester's property market spans from first-time buyer entry at £216,000 to Victorian and Georgian villas above £600,000, creating a diverse market where offer strategy depends heavily on sub-area (ONS, Q4 2025). The city centre apartment market carries different dynamics to the suburban family home market - flats typically sell at 90-94% of asking, while houses at the Chester average of £305,000 sell at 93-97%.</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0;">Macclesfield at £300,000 average represents Cheshire's balanced market - neither aggressively competitive nor heavily discounted. Turnkey family homes sell faster than properties requiring work. Frodsham at £340,000 carries a village premium driven by quality of life, the Sandstone Trail, and limited housing stock. Properties in Frodsham sell faster than the Cheshire West average due to constrained supply.</p>

      <h3 style="font-family: Georgia, serif; font-size: 20px; font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; margin: 24px 0 12px 0;">Affordable Cheshire - Crewe, Northwich, and Warrington</h3>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Crewe at £185,000 average offers the strongest negotiation position in Cheshire, with properties regularly accepting 7-12% below asking (Rightmove, 2025). First-time buyers and investors dominate this market, and properties listed for 60+ days frequently accept revised offers. Northwich ranges from £141,500 in Witton to £220,000 average, with regeneration projects adding upside potential that the current asking prices do not yet reflect.</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0;">Warrington at £245,000 sits between the affordable and mid-Cheshire tiers due to strong commuter demand for Manchester and Liverpool. New build developments in Warrington create direct competition between developers and private sellers - developers often include incentives (stamp duty contribution, upgrades, legal fees paid) that effectively reduce the purchase cost by 3-5% without a visible price reduction.</p>

      <h3 style="font-family: Georgia, serif; font-size: 20px; font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; margin: 24px 0 12px 0;">Seasonal patterns and the spring 2026 outlook</h3>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Cheshire property listings peak in March-April and September-October based on Rightmove listing volume data, concentrating buyer competition into these windows and reducing negotiation leverage compared to quieter months. January and July-August produce fewer new listings but also fewer competing buyers, making these months favourable for negotiation on stale properties.</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Mortgage rates on new fixed deals fell below 4% for both two-year and five-year terms by January 2026 (Bank of England Monetary Policy Report, February 2026). The FCA's revised stress-test floor of 6.5%, down from the 8.5% applied through 2023, increased maximum borrowing capacity for buyers at median Cheshire income levels.</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0;">Chester, Macclesfield, and Frodsham properties in the £250,000-£400,000 bracket face more competition in spring 2026 than at any point in 2025. Savills projects 5.5% capital growth for the North West in 2026 (Savills UK Residential Forecast, November 2025).</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Sealed Bids -->
  <section id="sealed-bids" class="section-pad">
    <div class="section-inner" style="max-width: 720px;">
      <span class="section-label">Cheshire sealed bid process</span>
      <h2 style="font-family: Georgia, serif; font-size: clamp(22px, 3vw, 30px); font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; line-height: 1.25; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">What are sealed bids and best-and-final offers in Cheshire?</h2>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><strong>Sealed bids require all interested buyers to submit their highest offer in writing by a fixed deadline, with the seller reviewing all bids simultaneously before selecting the winning buyer</strong> (NAEA Propertymark). The process differs from an auction - the seller is not obligated to accept the highest bid and can weigh buyer position, chain length, completion timeline, and proof of funds alongside the offer amount.</p>

      <h3 style="font-family: Georgia, serif; font-size: 20px; font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; margin: 24px 0 12px 0;">When do Cheshire agents use sealed bids?</h3>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Cheshire estate agents initiate sealed bids when three or more buyers express serious interest, typically within the first 7-14 days of listing (NAEA Propertymark). The practice is most common in the Golden Triangle for detached properties, period homes in Knutsford, and any property with a feature that creates scarcity - large plots, river frontage, or uninterrupted rural views.</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0;">Mid-Cheshire agents use sealed bids less frequently, typically for properties priced below the area average that attract first-time buyer demand. Sealed bids are rare in Crewe and Northwich unless a property is priced significantly below market value to attract investor interest.</p>

      <h3 style="font-family: Georgia, serif; font-size: 20px; font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; margin: 24px 0 12px 0;">How to structure a best-and-final offer</h3>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">A best-and-final offer includes five elements: the offer amount, proof of funds (AiP or bank statement), solicitor details confirming they are instructed, the proposed completion timeline, and a covering letter.</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">The covering letter is not a formality. Sellers of family homes in Knutsford and Chester routinely select buyers who demonstrate genuine intention to live in the property over investors offering 2-3% more.</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0;">Offer an exact figure (£487,500) rather than a round number (£490,000). Exact figures signal that the buyer has calculated the maximum based on their budget, not picked an arbitrary number. State a specific completion date ("within 8 weeks of exchange") rather than a vague timeline ("as soon as possible").</p>

      <h3 style="font-family: Georgia, serif; font-size: 20px; font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; margin: 24px 0 12px 0;">Proof of funds and mortgage agreement in principle</h3>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0;">A mortgage agreement in principle (AiP) confirms borrowing capacity but is not a mortgage offer - the lender has not yet valued the property or completed full underwriting. An AiP takes 24-48 hours from most lenders and is valid for 60-90 days.</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0;">Cash buyers provide a bank statement dated within 30 days showing available funds. In competitive Golden Triangle sealed bids, buyers with a full mortgage offer (not just an AiP) and a named solicitor are prioritised because they reduce the seller's risk of the transaction failing at the mortgage stage.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Gazumping -->
  <section id="gazumping" class="section-pad" style="background-color: #FFFFFF; border-top: 1px solid #E5E0D8; border-bottom: 1px solid #E5E0D8;">
    <div class="section-inner" style="max-width: 720px;">
      <span class="section-label">Cheshire gazumping protection</span>
      <h2 style="font-family: Georgia, serif; font-size: clamp(22px, 3vw, 30px); font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; line-height: 1.25; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">What is gazumping and how can Cheshire buyers protect themselves?</h2>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><strong>Cheshire buyers face gazumping risk when a seller accepts a higher offer from a second buyer after already accepting the first buyer's offer - a practice that is legal in England because accepted offers carry no contractual obligation until exchange</strong> (Law Society). The first buyer loses their conveyancing fees (£500-£1,800), survey costs (£400-£1,500), and mortgage arrangement fees - averaging £2,700 in total (HomeOwners Alliance, 2025). Four strategies reduce this risk between offer acceptance and exchange.</p>

      <h3 style="font-family: Georgia, serif; font-size: 20px; font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; margin: 24px 0 12px 0;">Four strategies to reduce gazumping risk in Cheshire</h3>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Cheshire buyers reduce gazumping exposure by acting on four points in the vulnerability window between offer acceptance and exchange. Speed of conveyancing, direct communication with the seller's agent, removing the property from the market, and first-offer commitment together address the conditions that allow a competing bid to succeed.</p>
      <div style="display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 12px; margin-bottom: 20px;">
        {[
          { strategy: 'Move fast on conveyancing', detail: 'Instruct your solicitor the same day as offer acceptance. Have your mortgage AiP in place before offering. Book the survey within 48 hours. Every day between acceptance and exchange is a day the seller can receive a competing offer.' },
          { strategy: 'Request the property is taken off the market', detail: 'Ask the agent to remove the listing from Rightmove and Zoopla once your offer is accepted. Sellers are not obligated to agree, but most will if the buyer demonstrates commitment through speed and communication. A property still marketed as "For Sale" invites competing interest.' },
          { strategy: 'Stay in regular contact', detail: 'Contact the estate agent weekly for progress updates. Silence from the buyer signals disinterest to the seller and agent. A seller who feels the buyer is engaged and progressing is less likely to entertain a second offer.' },
          { strategy: 'Make your best offer first', detail: 'An offer at 92% that gets revised to 95% after a competing bid appears signals that the buyer had more budget available. Offering your genuine maximum from the start reduces the incentive for the seller to test the market further.' },
        ].map((item) => (
          <div style="border: 1px solid #E5E0D8; padding: 16px 20px;">
            <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 15px; font-weight: 600; color: #1C1C1E; margin: 0 0 6px 0;">{item.strategy}</p>
            <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; color: #444444; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0;">{item.detail}</p>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>

      <h3 style="font-family: Georgia, serif; font-size: 20px; font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; margin: 24px 0 12px 0;">Lock-out agreements and exclusivity periods for Cheshire buyers</h3>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">A lock-out agreement is a written contract where the seller agrees not to negotiate with other buyers for a fixed period - typically 2-4 weeks (Law Society). The agreement gives the buyer exclusivity to complete searches and surveys without the risk of gazumping during that window. Lock-out agreements are legally binding if they specify a fixed duration and both parties sign.</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0;">Golden Triangle sellers rarely agree to lock-out terms - in a seller's market, a fixed exclusivity window removes the possibility of a competing offer arriving at full or above-asking price. Mid-Cheshire and affordable market sellers are more receptive, particularly for properties that have been listed for 60+ days. The buyer's solicitor drafts the agreement at a typical cost of £150-£300.</p>

      <h3 style="font-family: Georgia, serif; font-size: 20px; font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; margin: 24px 0 12px 0;">Home Buyer Protection Insurance</h3>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0;">Home Buyer Protection Insurance covers the buyer's abortive costs if the transaction falls through for reasons outside their control - gazumping, seller withdrawal, or chain collapse (HomeOwners Alliance, 2025). Policies start from £74 and cover conveyancing fees, survey costs, and mortgage arrangement fees up to a combined limit of £1,500-£3,000.</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0;">The policy does not cover the buyer withdrawing voluntarily or the mortgage lender declining to lend. Booking a <a href="/buying-guide/survey-types-cheshire" style="color: #3D5A3E;">property survey</a> early and taking out protection insurance together reduce the financial exposure of the subject-to-contract vulnerability window.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Estate Agent Duties -->
  <section id="estate-agent" class="section-pad">
    <div class="section-inner" style="max-width: 720px;">
      <span class="section-label">Estate agent legal duties</span>
      <h2 style="font-family: Georgia, serif; font-size: clamp(22px, 3vw, 30px); font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; line-height: 1.25; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">What does the Cheshire estate agent do with your offer?</h2>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><strong>Cheshire estate agents act for the seller, not the buyer - but are bound by the Estate Agents Act 1979 to present all offers promptly to the vendor and not discriminate between buyers</strong> (National Trading Standards). The agent earns commission (typically 1-1.5% of the sale price in Cheshire) from the seller, creating a financial incentive to achieve the highest possible price.</p>

      <h3 style="font-family: Georgia, serif; font-size: 20px; font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; margin: 24px 0 12px 0;">How does the Estate Agents Act 1979 protect Cheshire buyers?</h3>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Section 21 of the Estate Agents Act 1979 requires the agent to promptly pass on all offers to the seller, including offers received after one has been accepted. The agent cannot refuse to present an offer because the buyer is not using the agent's in-house mortgage broker or preferred solicitor. Failure to forward an offer is a criminal offence under the Act.</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0;">The Consumer Protection from Unfair Trading Regulations 2008 require agents to disclose material information: structural defects they are aware of, planning applications affecting the property, and any personal interest in the transaction.</p>

      <h3 style="font-family: Georgia, serif; font-size: 20px; font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; margin: 24px 0 12px 0;">What information strengthens your Cheshire offer to the agent?</h3>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">The estate agent assesses buyer quality alongside the offer amount. Providing four pieces of information at the time of offering strengthens your position: mortgage agreement in principle or proof of cash funds, name and contact details of your instructed solicitor, your chain status (first-time buyer, chain-free, or details of your chain), and your proposed completion timeline.</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0;">A chain-free buyer at 95% of asking price is often preferred over a buyer in a three-property chain at 98%. The agent advises the seller on transaction risk, and chain length is the primary risk factor. First-time buyers carry no chain by definition, making them attractive to sellers despite typically offering at the lower end of the range.</p>

      <h3 style="font-family: Georgia, serif; font-size: 20px; font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; margin: 24px 0 12px 0;">What do NAEA Propertymark and the Property Ombudsman cover?</h3>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0;"><a href="https://www.propertymark.co.uk/" style="color: #3D5A3E;" rel="nofollow noopener">NAEA Propertymark</a> members follow a code of practice requiring transparent fee disclosure, honest property descriptions, and prompt offer handling. The Property Ombudsman (TPO) provides a free complaints resolution service for buyers and sellers.</p>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0;">All estate agents in England are legally required to belong to a government-approved redress scheme - either TPO or the Property Redress Scheme (PRS). Verify redress scheme membership and check complaints history on the TPO website before choosing a Cheshire agent.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FAQ Accordion -->
  <section id="faq" class="section-pad" style="background-color: #FFFFFF; border-top: 1px solid #E5E0D8; border-bottom: 1px solid #E5E0D8;">
    <div class="section-inner" style="max-width: 800px;">
      <span class="section-label">Cheshire buyer FAQ</span>
      <h2 style="font-family: Georgia, serif; font-size: clamp(22px, 3vw, 30px); font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; line-height: 1.25; margin: 0 0 16px 0;">Offer questions for Cheshire buyers</h2>
      <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0 0 24px 0;">Common questions covering offer amounts by area, sealed bids, gazumping, mortgage readiness, and remote offers for buyers relocating to Cheshire.</p>
      <div>
        {faqs.map((faq, index) => (
          <details style={`border-top: ${index === 0 ? '2px solid #3D5A3E' : '1px solid #E5E0D8'};`}>
            <summary style="padding: 20px 0; cursor: pointer; font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 600; color: #1C1C1E; line-height: 1.4; list-style: none; display: flex; justify-content: space-between; align-items: center; gap: 16px;">
              {faq.question}
              <span style="font-family: Georgia, serif; font-size: 20px; color: #C4933F; flex-shrink: 0;">+</span>
            </summary>
            <div style="padding-bottom: 24px;">
              <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.75; color: #444444; margin: 0;">{faq.answer}</p>
            </div>
          </details>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Next Step Callout -->
  <section class="section-pad">
    <div class="section-inner" style="max-width: 720px;">
      <div style="border-left: 3px solid #3D5A3E; background-color: rgba(61, 90, 62, 0.04); padding: 24px 28px;">
        <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; font-weight: 700; color: #3D5A3E; margin: 0 0 8px 0; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.05em;">What happens after your offer is accepted</p>
        <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.7; color: #444444; margin: 0;">
          An accepted offer triggers the <a href="/buying-guide/conveyancing-cheshire" style="color: #3D5A3E;">conveyancing process</a> - local authority searches, the mandatory Cheshire Salt Search, pre-contract enquiries, and exchange of contracts. The typical Cheshire conveyancing timeline runs 8-12 weeks from SSTC to completion. <a href="/buying-guide/stamp-duty-cheshire" style="color: #3D5A3E;">Stamp duty</a> is calculated on the final agreed price and paid within 14 days of completion. Book a <a href="/buying-guide/survey-types-cheshire" style="color: #3D5A3E;">property survey</a> within 48 hours of acceptance to protect your position and identify defects before committing to the purchase.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Related Spokes -->
  <section class="section-pad" style="border-top: 1px solid #E5E0D8;">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <span class="section-label">Further Cheshire guides</span>
      <h2 style="font-family: Georgia, serif; font-size: clamp(22px, 3vw, 30px); font-weight: 700; color: #1C1C1E; line-height: 1.25; margin: 0 0 28px 0;">Related Cheshire buying guides</h2>
      <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(260px, 1fr)); gap: 20px;">
        {relatedSpokes.map((spoke) => (
          <a href={spoke.href} class="pillar-card" style="text-decoration: none; display: block;">
            <span style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 11px; font-weight: 700; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.1em; color: #3D5A3E; margin-bottom: 10px; display: block;">{spoke.tag}</span>
            <p style="font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; font-weight: 600; color: #1C1C1E; margin: 0; line-height: 1.4;">{spoke.label}</p>
          </a>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <script>
    const areaSelect = document.getElementById('offer-area') as HTMLSelectElement;
    const conditionSelect = document.getElementById('offer-condition') as HTMLSelectElement;
    const daysSelect = document.getElementById('offer-days') as HTMLSelectElement;
    const positionSelect = document.getElementById('offer-position') as HTMLSelectElement;
    const calcBtn = document.getElementById('offer-calc-btn') as HTMLButtonElement;
    const resultDiv = document.getElementById('offer-result') as HTMLElement;
    const rangeEl = document.getElementById('offer-range') as HTMLElement;
    const riskEl = document.getElementById('offer-risk') as HTMLElement;
    const tacticalEl = document.getElementById('offer-tactical') as HTMLElement;
    const checklistEl = document.getElementById('offer-checklist') as HTMLElement;

    interface OfferResult {
      low: number;
      high: number;
      risk: string;
      riskColor: string;
      tactical: string;
      checklist: string[];
    }

    function calculateOffer(): OfferResult {
      const area = areaSelect.value;
      const condition = conditionSelect.value;
      const days = daysSelect.value;
      const position = positionSelect.value;

      // Base range: 90-95%
      let low = 90;
      let high = 95;

      // Area adjustments
      if (area === 'golden-triangle') { low += 5; high += 8; }
      else if (area === 'chester') { low += 1; high += 3; }
      else if (area === 'mid-cheshire') { low += 0; high += 1; }
      else if (area === 'affordable') { low -= 2; high -= 1; }

      // Condition adjustments
      if (condition === 'turnkey') { low += 2; high += 5; }
      else if (condition === 'light-refurb') { low += 0; high += 0; }
      else if (condition === 'major-renovation') { low -= 10; high -= 5; }
      else if (condition === 'new-build') { low += 1; high += 3; }

      // Days on market adjustments
      if (days === 'under-14') { low += 2; high += 3; }
      else if (days === '14-60') { low += 0; high += 0; }
      else if (days === '60-120') { low -= 3; high -= 2; }
      else if (days === '120-plus') { low -= 8; high -= 5; }

      // Position adjustments (mostly tactical notes, minor range impact)
      if (position === 'in-chain') { low -= 1; high -= 1; }

      // Clamp
      low = Math.max(70, Math.min(low, 105));
      high = Math.max(low + 2, Math.min(high, 110));

      // Gazumping risk
      let risk = 'Medium';
      let riskColor = '#C4933F';
      if (area === 'golden-triangle' && days === 'under-14') { risk = 'High'; riskColor = '#C44B3F'; }
      else if (area === 'golden-triangle') { risk = 'High'; riskColor = '#C44B3F'; }
      else if (area === 'affordable' && days === '120-plus') { risk = 'Low'; riskColor = '#3D5A3E'; }
      else if (days === '120-plus') { risk = 'Low'; riskColor = '#3D5A3E'; }
      else if (area === 'affordable') { risk = 'Low'; riskColor = '#3D5A3E'; }

      // Tactical notes
      let tactical = '';
      if (area === 'golden-triangle' && condition === 'turnkey' && days === 'under-14') {
        tactical = 'Golden Triangle turnkey properties under 14 days rarely accept below asking price. Consider offering at or above asking price with proof of mortgage offer (not just AiP) and an instructed solicitor. Sealed bids are likely if other buyers are interested.';
      } else if (area === 'golden-triangle') {
        tactical = 'Golden Triangle properties attract strong competition. Strengthen your offer with a covering letter, named solicitor, and proof of funds. Period properties in Knutsford and detached homes in Wilmslow are the most contested segments.';
      } else if (area === 'affordable' && condition === 'major-renovation' && days === '120-plus') {
        tactical = 'A long-listed renovation property in this price bracket offers maximum negotiation room. The seller has likely received feedback on condition issues from previous viewers. Present a costed renovation schedule with your offer to demonstrate serious intent and justify the reduction.';
      } else if (area === 'affordable') {
        tactical = 'Affordable Cheshire markets favour buyers with 5-12% below asking regularly accepted. Properties listed for 60+ days carry the strongest negotiation position. New build developers in Warrington and Crewe may offer incentives (stamp duty contribution, upgrades) worth 3-5% of the asking price.';
      } else if (area === 'chester') {
        tactical = 'Chester\'s diverse market ranges from £216,000 FTB entry to £600,000+ villas. City centre flats sell at 90-94% of asking; suburban family homes at 93-97%. Research sold prices at the postcode level - Chester ward averages vary by up to £150,000.';
      } else if (condition === 'major-renovation') {
        tactical = 'Quantify renovation costs before offering: new roof (£5,000-£15,000), rewiring (£3,000-£5,000), damp treatment (£2,000-£8,000). Present itemised estimates with your offer to justify the reduction. The survey will confirm or adjust these figures.';
      } else if (days === '120-plus') {
        tactical = 'Properties listed for 120+ days have typically been overpriced, have a defect deterring buyers, or the market has moved since listing. Check the price history for previous reductions. The seller\'s motivation increases with time on market.';
      } else {
        tactical = 'Mid-Cheshire offers a balanced market with moderate negotiation room. Turnkey family homes move faster than properties requiring work. Strengthen your position by having your solicitor instructed and survey booked within 48 hours of offer acceptance.';
      }

      // Buyer position note appended
      if (position === 'ftb') {
        tactical += ' As a first-time buyer with no chain, you carry lower transaction risk than chain buyers - highlight this to the agent.';
      } else if (position === 'chain-free') {
        tactical += ' Chain-free buyers are the strongest position type. Sellers and agents prioritise chain-free offers because they eliminate the primary cause of transaction failure.';
      } else if (position === 'in-chain') {
        tactical += ' Being in a chain reduces your offer strength. Consider whether you can sell your current property first to become chain-free, or negotiate a longer completion timeline to account for chain dependencies.';
      } else if (position === 'investor') {
        tactical += ' Investor offers are assessed on speed and certainty rather than emotional connection. Provide proof of funds immediately and set a specific completion date.';
      }

      // Checklist
      const checklist = [
        'Mortgage agreement in principle or proof of cash funds ready',
        'Solicitor instructed and confirmed (name and contact details)',
        'Survey type selected: RICS Level 2 (£400-£1,000) or Level 3 (£630-£1,500)',
        'Land Registry sold prices checked for the target postcode',
        'Total budget ceiling calculated including SDLT, survey, and conveyancing fees',
      ];
      if (area === 'golden-triangle') {
        checklist.push('Covering letter prepared for sealed bid scenario');
      }
      if (risk === 'High') {
        checklist.push('Home Buyer Protection Insurance considered (from £74)');
      }

      return { low, high, risk, riskColor, tactical, checklist };
    }

    calcBtn.addEventListener('click', () => {
      const result = calculateOffer();

      rangeEl.textContent = `${result.low}-${result.high}%`;
      riskEl.textContent = result.risk;
      riskEl.style.color = result.riskColor;
      tacticalEl.textContent = result.tactical;

      checklistEl.innerHTML = result.checklist.map(item =>
        `<div style="display: flex; align-items: flex-start; gap: 8px; font-family: Inter, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; color: #444444;">
          <span style="color: #3D5A3E; font-weight: 700; flex-shrink: 0;">&#10003;</span>
          <span>${item}</span>
        </div>`
      ).join('');

      resultDiv.style.display = 'block';
    });
  </script>
</BaseLayout>
